Complex64  = 2*Float32 Complex128 = 2*Float64 Channel    = Uintptr Function   = Uintptr Interface  = 2*Uintptr Map        = Uintptr Rune       = Int32 Slice      = Uintptr + 2*Int String     = Uintptr + Int )

Michael T. Jones

I think there is too much duplication here.  I don't see a need to duplicate the Go code at all.  Just duplicate the C function. You can do this by writing getgrouplist_darwin.c and getgrouplist_unix.c.  You can write an extern declaration in lookup_unix.c.  Pick a type to use in lookup_unix.c, probably gid_t, and pass a gid_t* to the C function.  Have the Darwin version rewrite the results to int.

The basic problem here is that Linux and BSD define getgrouplist as:

int getgrouplist(const char *name, gid_t gid, gid_t* groups, int* ngroups)

and Darwin defines it as:

int getgrouplist(const char *name, int gid, int* groups, int* ngroups)

AFAICT, gid_t is not guaranteed to be an int, but happens to be on Darwin. So if I defined a C function that wraps it like:

int mygetgrouplist(const char *name, gid_t gid, gid_t** groups, int* ngroups)

To be safe, I would have to allocate a different internal buffer and copy it over into the passed in groups buffer.  Seems unfair to always add an extra allocation to Darwin.  I tried a few other ways of reducing duplication, but they made the code harder to read than this approach.
